  "prompt": "What is meant by monopolistic competition?",
  "response": "Monopolistic competition is a market structure characterized by the following key features:\n\n1. Many sellers\n- Numerous firms competing in the market\n- Each firm sells similar but slightly differentiated products\n- Low barriers to entry and exit\n\n2. Product differentiation\n- Firms offer products with unique characteristics\n- Slight variations in quality, design, brand, or marketing\n- Creates a sense of product uniqueness\n\n3. Price-setting ability\n- Firms have some control over pricing\n- Can set prices slightly higher due to product differentiation\n- Limited market power compared to pure monopolies\n\n4. Imperfect competition\n- Products are similar but not identical\n- Firms have some pricing flexibility\n- Compete through non-price strategies like advertising and branding\n\n5. Examples of industries\n- Restaurants\n- Clothing retailers\n- Beauty salons\n- Consumer electronics\n- Personal care products\n\n6. Characteristics\n- Firms are price makers, not price takers\n- Relatively easy market entry\n- Profits are typically moderate\n- High consumer choice\n- Firms compete on quality and perceived differences\n\nMonopolistic competition represents a market structure that balances aspects of perfect competition and monopoly, offering consumers variety and firms some pricing flexibility.",
